\v 1 God, foreign nations have come into \add the land you gave as an\add* inheritance.
\q1 They have defiled your holy temple.
\q1 They have turned Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add* into a heap of ruins.
\q1
\v 2 They have given the dead bodies of your servants as food to the birds in the skies—
\q1 the bodies of your faithful ones to the animals on the ground.
\q1
\v 3 They’ve shed their blood around Yerushalem like water,
\q1 and there wasn’t anyone to bury them.
\q1
\v 4 We have become a reproach for our neighbours—
\q1 mocked and scorned by those around us.
\q1
\v 5 How long, Yahweh? Will you stay angry forever?
\q1 For how long will your jealous anger burn like fire?
\q1
\v 6 Pour out your rage on the nations that don’t know you
\q1 and on the kingdoms that don’t \add pray to you\add*,
\q1
\v 7 because they’ve devoured Yakov \add (Jacob/Israel)\add*
\q1 and destroyed his villages.
\q1
\v 8 Don’t hold the sins of our ancestors against us.
\q1 May \add we experience your acts of mercy\add*, because we’re very \add discouraged\add*.
\q1
\v 9 Help us, God of our salvation, for the sake of the glory of your name.
\q1 Save us and forgive our sins for the sake of your \add reputation\add*.
\q1
\v 10 Why should the nations say, “Where is their God?”
\q1 Let your servants’ blood that was shed
\q1 be avenged on the nations before our eyes.
\q1
\v 11 May the groans of the prisoners come before you.
\q1 Keep \add those condemned to\add* death alive with the greatness of your power.
\q1
\v 12 Pay back seven times as much into the laps of our neighbouring countries
\q1 as \add repayment for\add* the insults with which they have insulted you, Lord.
\q1
\v 13 So we your people, and sheep of your pasture,
\q1 will give you thanks forever.
\q1 We will tell your praises to all generations.
\c 80
\s1 A prayer for national restoration
\d For the musical director: a song by Asaf to be sung to the tune of ‘Lilies of Agreement.’
\q1
\v 1 Pay attention, Yisrael’s shepherd.
\q1 You who lead Yosef \add (Joseph/Israel)\add* like a flock;
\q1 You who sit above the winged creatures \add on the sacred chest\add*, shine on us!
\q1
\v 2 In the sight of Efraim and Benyamin and Menashsheh, stir up your power.
\q1 Come and save us.
\q1
\v 3 God, restore us;
\q1 \add Show us your favour\add* and then we’ll be saved.
\q1
\v 4 Army commander Yahweh,
\q1 how long will you be angry at your people when they pray?
\q1
\v 5 You have fed them with bread \add made from\add* tears
\q1 and given them tears to drink in great quantities.
\q1
\v 6 You make us something for our neighbours to argue over,
\q1 and our enemies \add laugh about\add* us among themselves.
\q1
\v 7 Army commander God, restore us.
\q1 \add Show us your favour\add* and then we’ll be saved.
\q1
\v 8 You brought a grapevine out of Egypt.
\q1 You drove out nations then transplanted it.
\q1
\v 9 You cleared the land for it,
\q1 →and \add the grapevine\add* took root and filled the land.
\q1
\v 10 The mountains were covered with its shade.
\q1 God’s cedars \add were covered\add* by its branches.
\q1
\v 11 It sent out its branches as far as the sea
\q1 and its shoots to the \add Euphrates\add* River.
\q1
\v 12 Why have you broken down \add the walls around it\add*
\q1 →so that all who pass by along the road pick its fruit?
\q1
\v 13 The boars out of the forest ruin it,
\q1 and the animals in the countryside feed on it.
\q1
\v 14 Turn back, army commander God.
\q1 Look down from heaven and take notice and take care of this grapevine.
\q1
\v 15 This is the root that you planted \add by your power\add*—
\q1 the shoot that you made grow.
\q1
\v 16 It has been cut down and burnt.
\q1 They perish at your rebuke.
\q1
\v 17 May your hand be on the man \add you’ve given your power to\add*—
\q1 on the son of humanity who you made strong for yourself.
\q1
\v 18 Then we won’t turn away from you.
\q1 Revive us, and we’ll \add always\add* \add pray to you\add*.
\q1
\v 19 Army command Yahweh God, restore us.
\q1 \add Show us your favour\add* and then we’ll be saved.
\c 81
\s1 Thanking God for relief
\d For the musical director: a song by Asaf \add to be accompanied by\add* stringed instrument.\f + \fr 81:0 \ft In Hebrew, ‘Gitit’ could be an instrument or type of voice.\f*
\q1
\v 1 Sing aloud to God our strength.
\q1 Shout out to Yacob’s God with happiness.
\q1
\v 2 Sing a song and play the tambourine—
\q1 the pleasant lyre with the harp.
\q1
\v 3 Blow the trumpet on the day of the new moon,
\q1 on the day of the full moon, when our celebration begins,
\q1
\v 4 because it’s a statute for Israel—
\q1 a decree given by Yakov’s God.
\q1
\v 5 He issued it as a regulation in Yosef \add (Joseph, but referring to Yisrael)\add*
\q1 when he went against Egypt,
\q1 where I heard a voice that I didn’t recognize:
\q1
\v 6 “I removed the burden from his shoulder.
\q1 His hands were freed from \add having to hold\add* the basket.
\q1
\v 7 In your distress you called out, and I helped you.
\q1 I answered you from a dark thundercloud.
\q1 I tested you at the waters of Meribah. \qs (Instrumental break.)\qs*
\q1
\v 8 Listen, my people, \add yes,\add* I’ll warn you, Israel.
\q1 If you would only listen to me.
\q1
\v 9 There mustn’t be any foreign god among you.
\q1 You mustn’t worship any foreign god.
\q1
\v 10 I’m your God Yahweh who brought you out of Egypt.
\q1 Open your mouth wide, and I’ll fill it.
\q1
\v 11 \add But\add* my people didn’t listen to my words.
\q1 Yisrael didn’t obey me.
\q1
\v 12 So I \add let them go\add* their own stubborn way
\q1 so that they could do whatever seemed okay to them.
\q1
\v 13 If only my people would listen to me.
\q1 If only my people would \add follow\add* my ways.
\q1
\v 14 \add If they did,\add* I’d quickly subdue their enemies
\q1 and \add use my strength\add* against \add those who oppress them\add*.
\q1
\v 15 May those who hate Yahweh cringe in fear before him.
\q1 May they be humiliated forever.
\q1
\v 16 I would feed Yisrael with the finest \add bread\add*.
\q1 I would satisfy you with honey out of the rock.”
\c 82
\s1 God the defender
\d A song by Asaf.
\q1
\v 1 God stands in the divine assembly.
\q1 He renders judgement among the gods.
\q1
\v 2 For how long will you judge unjustly
\q1 and show favouritism to the wicked? \qs (Instrumental break.)\qs*
\q1
\v 3 Defend the poor and the fatherless.
\q1 Maintain the rights of those who’re afflicted and destitute.
\q1
\v 4 Rescue the poor and needy—
\q1 \add help them escape from the control of the wicked\add* \add people\add*.
\q1
\v 5 They neither know nor understand.
\q1 They wander around in the darkness.
\q1 All the earth’s foundations crumble.
\q1
\v 6 I said, “You are ‘gods’,
\q1 and all of you are sons of the highest \add one\add*.
\q1
\v 7 Nevertheless you will die like men
\q1 and fall like one of the \add leaders\add*.”
\q1
\v 8 \add Take action\add*, God, judge the earth,
\q1 because you have an inheritance in all the nations.
\c 83
\s1 Praying for victory over enemies
\d A song by Asaf.
\q1
\v 1 God, don’t be silent.
\q1 Don’t ignore us and remain unmoved, God.
\q1
\v 2 Look, your enemies are making a commotion,
\q1 and those who hate you \add starting to cause trouble\add*.
\q1
\v 3 They conspire against your people,
\q1 and plan together against your protected ones.
\q1
\v 4 They’ve said, “Come, and let’s destroy them as a nation,
\q1 →then the name of Yisrael will \add soon be forgotten\add*.”
\q1
\v 5 They schemed together with \add a unified\add* strategy.
\q1 they made an alliance against you—
\q1
\v 6 the tents of Edom and the Ishmaelites,
\q1 of Moab and the Hagrites,
\q2
\v 7 Gebal, Ammon, Amalek,
\q1 and also Philistia and the inhabitants of Tsor.
\q2
\v 8 Assyria also has joined with them.
\q1 They have become an arm for the descendants of Lot. \qs (Instrumental break.)\qs*
\q1
\v 9 Do to them as you did to Midyan,\x + \xo 83:9 \xt Jdg 7–8.\x*
\q1 as you did to Sisera and to Yabin at the Kishon River.\x + \xo 83:9 \xt Jdg 4–5.\x*
\q2
\v 10 They perished at Eyndor
\q1 →and became like dung on the ground.
\q1
\v 11 Make their nobles like Orev and Zeev,
\q1 and all their princes like Zevah and Tsalmunna.
\q1
\v 12 They said, “Let’s take God’s pastures for ourselves.”
\q1
\v 13 My God, make them like the whirling dust.
\q1 \add Make them\add* like chaff \add blown around by\add* the wind,
\q1
\v 14 like the fire that burns a forest,
\q1 \add or\add* like a flame that sets mountains on fire.
\q1
\v 15 Chase them with your strong wind,
\q1 and terrify them with your windstorm.
\q1
\v 16 \add Cause them to be very ashamed\add*
\q1 so that they might \add want to find out more about you\add*, Yahweh.
\q1
\v 17 May they be put to shame and be terrified forever.
\q1 May they perish in disgrace.
\q1
\v 18 Then they will know that you alone, Yahweh,
\q1 are to be honoured as the highest \add one\add* over all the earth.
\c 84
\s1 Longing to be in Yahweh’s courtyards
\d For the musical director: a song by Korah’s descendants \add to be accompanied by\add* stringed instrument.\f + \fr 84:0 \ft In Hebrew, ‘Gitit’ could be an instrument or type of voice.\f*
\q1
\v 1 How lovely is the place where you live,
\q1 army commander Yahweh.
\q1
\v 2 I long \add to be in\add* Yahweh’s \add temple\add* courtyards—my desire for them has made me exhausted.
\q1 My heart and all of my being call out to the living God.
\q1
\v 3 Even the sparrow has found herself a house
\q1 and the swallow a nest for herself where she may lay her young
